==English==

===Alternative forms===
* [[carefull]] (obsolete)

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|careful|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|carful|lang=ang}}, {{m|ang|ċearful||careful, anxious, curious, troubled}}, equivalent to {{suffix|care|ful|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈkɛːfəl/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-careful.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

#{{context|obsolete|lang=en}} Full of [[care]] or [[grief]]; [[sorrowful]], [[sad]].
#*{{RQ:Mlry MrtArthr1}}, Bk.V:
#*:‘Alas,’ sayde Sir Cadore, ‘now '''carefull''' is myne herte that now lyeth dede my cosyn that I beste loved.’
#{{context|obsolete|lang=en}} Full of [[cares]] or [[anxiety]]; [[worried]], [[troubled]].
#*'''1590''', {{w|Edmund Spenser}}, ''The Faerie Queene'', III.1:
#*:Where through long watch, and late daies weary toile, / She soundly slept, and '''carefull''' thoughts did quite assoile.
#Having care (for); [[attentive]] to [[potential]] [[danger]], [[error]] or [[harm]]; [[cautious]].
#:''He was a slow and '''careful''' driver.''
#[[conscientious|Conscientious]] and [[painstaking]]; [[meticulous]].
#:''They made a '''careful''' search of the crime scene.''

